# Function to extract all labels from the dataset
def get_labels(dataset):
    all_labels = []
    for _, labels in dataset:
        all_labels.append(labels.numpy())
    return np.concatenate(all_labels)
In[6]:

    keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(

        save_best_only=True,
        monitor="val_loss"
    ),
    
    # Early stopping to prevent overfitting
    EarlyStopping(
        monitor='val_loss',
        patience=10,               # Stop if no improvement for 10 epochs
        restore_best_weights=True  # Restore model to the best epoch
    ),
    
    # Learning rate reduction when plateauing
    ReduceLROnPlateau(
        monitor='val_loss',
        factor=0.5,                # Reduce LR by half
        patience=3,                # Wait 5 epochs before reducing
        min_lr=1e-6                # Don't go below this LR
    )
]

Summary of the Term Project: Pneumonia Detection

Training Overview

Three Models Were Trained:

  • Custom CNN
  • MobileNet
  • ResNet

Each Was Trained With Two Optimizers:

  • Adam
  • RMSProp

Each Model's Performance Was Evaluated On:

  • Accuracy
  • Classification Report
    • Precision
    • Recall
    • F1-Score
  • Confusion Matrix

Comparison and Insights

  • CNN (Adam) showed a high imbalance: excellent at detecting Pneumonia, but poor for Normal cases (Recall: 49%).
  • CNN (RMSProp) improved detection in both classes, reaching 90% accuracy, with more balanced recall (67% Normal, 98% Pneumonia).
  • MobileNet (Adam) delivered excellent overall performance: 90% accuracy, 96% precision on Normal, 99% recall on Pneumonia.
  • MobileNet (RMSProp) was weaker compared to its Adam counterpart (86.8% accuracy).
  • ResNet (Adam & RMSProp) showed stable behavior (8788% accuracy) but didn't outperform MobileNet (Adam).

Final Model Selection

Best Model: MobileNet with Adam Optimizer

Reason:

  • Highest precision (0.96 for Normal) and recall (0.99 for Pneumonia)
  • Balanced performance across both classes
  • Highest F1-scores among all models
  • Strong generalization with 90% accuracy

Conclusion

The training methodology correctly involved thorough evaluation across models and optimizers. While ResNet showed stability, MobileNet with Adam stood out as the most balanced and strongest model for real-world pneumonia detection tasks based on this dataset.Given the context, MobileNet with Adam was selected because it better minimizes false positives (wrongly diagnosing healthy individuals), which is critical in medical settings.
